{"cursor":"2090","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nAs a general term, a substance is said to be 'anhydrous' if it contains no\nwater. The way of achieving the anhydrous form differs from one substance to\nanother. That is to say, anhydrous matter is prepared or used as a form with no\nwater, and specifically the form of a chemical without water of crystallization.\n","linknr":111,"url":"Anhydrous","recorded":1362486092,"links":20,"instances":[],"pdf":[],"categories":["Chemical properties"],"headings":["Solvents","Gases","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[],"members":[],"related":["Water","Water_of_crystallization","Grignard_reaction","Wurtz_reaction","Hygroscopic","Sodium","Molecular_sieve","Potassium_hydroxide","Barium_oxide","Standard_conditions_of_temperature_and_pressure","Ammonia","Ammonium_hydroxide","Aqueous_solution","Hydrogen_chloride","Air-free_technique"]}